===Etymology===
From {{L.}} ''[[arbitrarius]]'', from ''[[arbiter]]'' - eye-witness, on-looker; judge, overseer, lord; executor. Mainly in legal context.

===Pronunciation===
* {{italbrac|[[RP]]}} {{IPA|/ˈɑːbɪtrəri/}}
* {{italbrac|US}} {{IPA|/ˈɑːrbɪtrɛri/}}
* {{audio|en-us-arbitrary.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adj}}

# determined by [[impulse]] rather than [[reason]]; [[heavy-handed]].
#: ''"The Russian trials were Stalin's purges, with which he attempted to consolidate his power. Like most people in the West, I believed these show trials to be the '''arbitrary''' acts of a cruel dictator."'' ([http://en.wikiquote.org/wiki/Einstein Max Born, Letters to Einstein])
# not based on any [[objective]] distinction
# chosen for no particularly reason, somewhat [[random]].
# {{math}} any and all possible.
#: ''The equation is true for an '''arbitrary''' value of x.''

====Usage notes====
* The word "arbitrary" does exactly mean "random", but it often used (sometimes incorrectly) in this sense.  More specifically, it it used to refer to decisions, for whcih there had not been any obviously correct choice.  For example, the decision to choose the age of 18 as the age for legal adulthood is not random but it is arbitrary, because other ages, like 19 or 21, could have been chosen, and there is nothing particular about the age 18 that makes it the correct choice.

